In .NET MAUI, use **Window lifecycle events** instead of the old `Application` overrides:

| Xamarin.Forms | .NET MAUI (Window) |
|---|---|
| `OnStart` | `Activated` (or `Created`) |
| `OnSleep` | `Stopped` |
| `OnResume` | `Resumed` |

Override `CreateWindow` in your `App` class:

```csharp
public partial class App : Application
{
    protected override Window CreateWindow(IActivationState? activationState)
    {
        var window = base.CreateWindow(activationState);

        window.Created += (s, e) => { /* one-time init */ };
        window.Stopped += (s, e) => { /* save state (was OnSleep) */ };
        window.Resumed += (s, e) => { /* restore state (was OnResume) */ };

        return window;
    }
}
```

**Key differences:**
- `Resumed` does **not** fire on first launch — the initial sequence is `Created` → `Activated`.
- On Android, the back button can skip `Stopped` and go straight to `Destroying`, so save critical state in both.
- The old `OnStart`/`OnSleep`/`OnResume` still compile for compatibility but bypass per-window events — avoid them in new MAUI code.
